Wash and dry produce. Trim and discard root end from @baby lettuce{1}; roughly chop.

Reserve ½ tsp pickle brine (1 tsp for 4 servings) in a #small bowl{}; drain and discard remaining brine and roughly chop @dill pickle{1}(sliced). Dice @tomato{1}.

Stir ½ tsp @fry seasoning{1%tbsp} and @sugar{¼%tsp} into #bowl{} with reserved pickle brine (1 tsp Fry Seasoning and ½ tsp sugar for 4). (You'll use the rest of the Fry Seasoning in the next step.)

> You'll use the rest of the Fry Seasoning in the next step.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @ground beef{10%oz}, remaining Fry Seasoning, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Stir in @beef stock concentrate{1} and ¼ cup water (⅓ cup for 4 servings). Cook, stirring, until liquid has absorbed and beef is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Transfer to a #plate{}.

Meanwhile, to bowl with pickle brine mixture, add @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, @ketchup{1}, and half the @Dijon mustard{2%tsp} (all for 4 servings). Stir until well combined.

Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

In a #large bowl{}, toss lettuce with half the dressing and half the tomato.

Divide salad between #bowls{}. Top with beef, @Monterey Jack cheese{¼%cup}, pickle, and remaining tomato. Drizzle with remaining dressing and serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.